<topic id="level_2_und_3_1">
  <title>Level 2 and 3</title>
  <body>
    <p>In both black letter and antiqua texts, two forms of the lower case letter <tt>s</tt> can
            occur: the <tt>long-s</tt> (<tt>ſ, U+017F, LATIN SMALL LETTER LONG S</tt>) and the
                <tt>round s</tt> (<tt>s, U+0073, LATIN SMALL LETTER S</tt>). They are differentiated
            in the transcription. </p>
    <p>The ligature of <tt>long-s</tt> and <tt>z</tt> is <b>not to dissolve</b> but to transcribe as ß
            (spoken sz). Exceptions and particularities are shown in the following table.</p>
    <p>
      <table frame="all" rowsep="1" colsep="1" id="table_j52_dhl_gz">
